`waitForEvent(target, eventName)` suspends the task until the specified DOM event fires on the given target element. Like `timeout()`, it is cancellation-aware — if the task is cancelled while waiting, the listener is automatically removed. This allows tasks to pause mid-execution waiting for user interaction without blocking the main thread.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, waitForProperty } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchProcessorComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matchData = null
  @tracked isDataReady = false

  loadMatchData = task(async () => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${this.args.matchId}`)
    this.matchData = await response.json()
    this.isDataReady = true
  })

  processMatchStats = task(async () => {
    // Wait until matchData is available
    await waitForProperty(this, 'isDataReady', true)

    // Now safe to use this.matchData
    const stats = {
      strikeRate: (this.matchData.runs / this.matchData.balls) * 100,
      runRate: this.matchData.runs / this.matchData.overs
    }
    return stats
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' this.loadMatchData.perform}}>Load Data</button>
    <button {{on 'click' this.processMatchStats.perform}}>Process Stats</button>
  </template>
}
```
`waitForProperty(object, propertyName, truthyValueOrPredicate)` suspends the task until the specified property on the object equals the given value (or satisfies the predicate function). It observes the property reactively, so it immediately resumes when the condition is met without polling. This is useful for coordinating between tasks with dependencies.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, all } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDashboardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked dashboardData = null

  fetchMatchInfo = task(async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    return response.json()
  })

  fetchTeamStats = task(async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/team-stats`)
    return response.json()
  })

  loadDashboard = task(async (matchId) => {
    const [matchInfo, teamStats] = await all([
      this.fetchMatchInfo.perform(matchId),
      this.fetchTeamStats.perform(matchId)
    ])

    this.dashboardData = { matchInfo, teamStats }
    return this.dashboardData
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.loadDashboard.perform @matchId)}}>
      Load Dashboard
    </button>
    {{#if this.loadDashboard.isRunning}}
      <p>Loading match dashboard...</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
`all()` from ember-concurrency is like `Promise.all()` but cancellation-aware. It takes an array of task instances or Promises and resolves with an array of results when all have completed. If the parent task is cancelled, all child tasks are also cancelled automatically. Use `all()` to parallelize independent async operations and reduce total wait time.

