Service tasks are accessed via the injected service reference. Call `.perform()` on the service's task just like a component task. The task's `isRunning`, `last.value`, and `last.error` are all accessible through the service in the template using `this.serviceName.taskName.isRunning`. Multiple components sharing the same service share the same task state.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerRatingComponent extends Component {
  // Task returns a computed value
  calculatePlayerRating = task(async (playerId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}/stats`)
    const stats = await response.json()

    // Compute and return the rating
    const rating = (
      (stats.battingAverage * 0.4) +
      (stats.strikeRate * 0.3) +
      (stats.fieldingRating * 0.3)
    ).toFixed(2)

    return {
      playerId,
      playerName: stats.name,
      rating: parseFloat(rating),
      breakdown: {
        batting: stats.battingAverage,
        striking: stats.strikeRate,
        fielding: stats.fieldingRating
      }
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.calculatePlayerRating.perform @playerId)}}>
      Calculate Rating
    </button>

    {{#if this.calculatePlayerRating.last.value}}
      <div class="mt-4 p-3 bg-yellow-50 rounded">
        <p class="font-bold">{{this.calculatePlayerRating.last.value.playerName}}</p>
        <p class="text-2xl">⭐ {{this.calculatePlayerRating.last.value.rating}}</p>
      </div>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Anything returned from the async task function is stored in `task.last.value` upon successful completion. You can return simple values, objects, or arrays. The return value is accessed in the template as `this.taskName.last.value` and is `undefined` while the task is running or before it has been performed.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchUpdaterComponent extends Component {
  @tracked errorMessage = null
  @tracked successMessage = null

  updateMatchScore = task(async (matchId, scoreData) => {
    this.errorMessage = null
    this.successMessage = null

    try {
      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`, {
        method: 'PUT',
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
        body: JSON.stringify(scoreData)
      })

      if (!response.ok) {
        throw new Error(`Server error: ${response.status}`)
      }

      const result = await response.json()
      this.successMessage = `Score updated: ${result.runs}/${result.wickets}`
      return result
    } catch (error) {
      this.errorMessage = error.message
      throw error // Re-throw so task.last.error is populated
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.errorMessage}}
      <p class="text-red-500">{{this.errorMessage}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if this.successMessage}}
      <p class="text-green-500">{{this.successMessage}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Use standard `try/catch` inside tasks for error handling. If you want the error to be available via `task.last.error`, re-throw it after catching. If you handle the error completely without re-throwing, `task.last.error` will remain `undefined` and the task will be considered successfully completed.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class FileExportComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isExporting = false
  @tracked exportUrl = null

  exportMatchData = task(async (matchId) => {
    this.isExporting = true
    let objectUrl = null

    try {
      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/export`)
      const blob = await response.blob()
      objectUrl = URL.createObjectURL(blob)
      this.exportUrl = objectUrl
      return objectUrl
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Export failed:', error)
      throw error
    } finally {
      // Always runs: success, failure, or cancellation
      this.isExporting = false
      // If we created a URL but something went wrong, clean it up
      if (objectUrl && !this.exportUrl) {
        URL.revokeObjectURL(objectUrl)
      }
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.exportMatchData.perform @matchId)}}>
      Export Data
    </button>
  </template>
}
```
The `finally` block in a task executes regardless of whether the task succeeded, threw an error, or was cancelled. This makes it the right place for cleanup operations like revoking object URLs, hiding loading indicators, or closing connections — operations that must always happen no matter how the task ended.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class AnalyticsComponent extends Component {
  loadMatchAnalytics = task(async (matchId) => {
    try {
      const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/analytics`)

      if (!response.ok) {
        throw new Error(`Analytics API error: ${response.status} ${response.statusText}`)
      }

      return response.json()
    } catch (error) {
      // Log the error for monitoring (e.g., Sentry)
      console.error('[MatchAnalytics] Failed to load:', {
        matchId,
        error: error.message,
        timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
      })

      // Re-throw so task.last.error is populated and template can react
      throw error
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.loadMatchAnalytics.perform @matchId)}}>
      Load Analytics
    </button>

    {{#if this.loadMatchAnalytics.last.error}}
      <p class="text-red-500">
        Failed: {{this.loadMatchAnalytics.last.error.message}}
      </p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Re-throwing after catching allows you to perform side effects (logging, analytics reporting, toast notifications) while still propagating the error to the task instance. If you swallow the error without re-throwing, `task.last.error` stays `undefined` and `task.last.value` also remains `undefined`, leaving the UI unable to distinguish success from failure.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchPageComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matchData = null
  @tracked highlights = null

  // Child tasks
  fetchMatchData = task(async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    return response.json()
  })

  fetchHighlights = task(async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/highlights`)
    return response.json()
  })

  // Parent task — performs child tasks
  loadMatchPage = task(async (matchId) => {
    // Step 1: Load match data
    this.matchData = await this.fetchMatchData.perform(matchId)

    // Step 2: Load highlights using match data
    this.highlights = await this.fetchHighlights.perform(matchId)

    return { matchData: this.matchData, highlights: this.highlights }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.loadMatchPage.perform @matchId)}}>
      Load Match Page
    </button>
    {{#if this.loadMatchPage.isRunning}}
      <p>Loading...</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Nested tasks — where one task `await`s another task's `.perform()` — create a parent-child relationship. When the parent task is cancelled, any awaited child task is also cancelled automatically. This cascading cancellation is safe and reliable, making nested tasks the preferred way to compose complex async workflows.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { registerDestructor } from '@ember/destroyable'

export default class DataSyncComponent extends Component {
  @tracked syncProgress = 0
  @tracked syncStatus = 'idle'

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args)
    registerDestructor(this, () => this.syncData.cancelAll())
  }

  syncData = task(async () => {
    this.syncStatus = 'syncing'
    this.syncProgress = 0

    try {
      const matches = await fetch('/api/matches/pending').then(r => r.json())

      for (const [index, match] of matches.entries()) {
        await fetch(`/api/matches/${match.id}/sync`, { method: 'POST' })
        this.syncProgress = Math.round(((index + 1) / matches.length) * 100)
        await timeout(100) // Allow cancellation between iterations
      }

      this.syncStatus = 'complete'
    } catch {
      this.syncStatus = 'cancelled'
    }
  })

  abort = () => this.syncData.cancelAll()

  <template>
    {{#if this.syncData.isIdle}}
      <button {{on 'click' this.syncData.perform}}>Start Sync</button>
    {{else}}
      <p>{{this.syncProgress}}% synced</p>
      <button {{on 'click' this.abort}} class="text-red-500">Abort</button>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
`cancelAll()` immediately stops all running task instances by throwing a `TaskCancelation` error inside the async function at the next `await` point. The task resumes in the `catch` block (or `finally`) where you can set a 'cancelled' status. Including periodic `await timeout(0)` or small delays in loops creates natural cancellation checkpoints.

