Calling `.perform()` in the constructor runs before the component's DOM is mounted and before Glimmer has finished setting up reactivity, which can lead to race conditions and stale renders. The correct pattern is to trigger the task using the `{{did-insert}}` modifier, which fires after the element is inserted into the DOM.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class VenueLoader extends Component {
  @tracked venue = null

  loadVenue = task(async (element) => {
    // element is the DOM node passed by did-insert
    const response = await fetch(`/api/venues/${this.args.venueId}`)
    if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Venue not found')
    this.venue = await response.json()
  })

  <template>
    <section {{did-insert (fn this.loadVenue.perform)}}>
      {{#if this.loadVenue.isRunning}}
        <p class="text-gray-400">Loading venue...</p>
      {{else if this.venue}}
        <h2>{{this.venue.name}}</h2>
        <p>City: {{this.venue.city}}</p>
        <p>Capacity: {{this.venue.capacity}}</p>
      {{/if}}
    </section>
  </template>
}
```
The `{{did-insert}}` modifier from `ember-render-modifiers` calls its callback once, immediately after the element is added to the DOM. Passing `(fn this.loadVenue.perform)` ensures the task starts at the right lifecycle moment. The modifier automatically passes the DOM element as the first argument to the callback, which the task receives as `element` (though it's often ignored).

