Early versions of ember-concurrency required actual `function*` generators with `yield` instead of `async/await`. Modern ember-concurrency v3+ accepts standard `async` functions and uses a Babel transform or native async iterator support to intercept each `await` internally. Conceptually, every `await` inside a task is a suspension point where ember-concurrency can check for cancellation before resuming. Understanding this mental model explains why cancellation is cooperative (only happens at `await` points) and why synchronous code between awaits cannot be interrupted.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

export default class LiveScoreWidget extends Component {
  @tracked matchId = null

  // Task reads @tracked property — re-runs when matchId changes
  fetchScore = task({ restartable: true }, async () => {
    if (!this.matchId) return null
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${this.matchId}/score`)
    return await res.json()
  })

