Ember Data's `store.query()`, `store.findRecord()`, and `store.findAll()` all return Promises, so they're directly awaitable inside tasks. Wrapping Ember Data calls in tasks gives you loading state, error handling, and cancellation that route `model()` hooks don't provide for component-level data fetching. Use tasks for data loaded in response to user interaction (tab switches, filters, search) and route `model()` for initial page data. Tasks also re-fetch correctly on argument changes when combined with `restartable`.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ❌ Performing in constructor — component not fully initialized
class BadMatchLoader extends Component {
  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args)
    // Template not rendered yet, DOM not ready
    // Errors may occur if task accesses services not yet fully initialized
    this.loadMatch.perform(args.matchId)
  }

  loadMatch = task(async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json())
  })
}

// ✅ Use a modifier or template helper instead
export default class GoodMatchLoader extends Component {
  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  <template>
    {{! didInsert equivalent: run task after component renders }}
    <div {{(modifier to run task on insert)}}>
      {{#if this.loadMatch.isRunning}}
        <p>Loading...</p>
      {{else}}
        <p>{{this.loadMatch.last.value.teams}}</p>
      {{/if}}
    </div>
    {{! Or: trigger from template directly when args are present }}
    {{#if @matchId}}
      {{(perform this.loadMatch @matchId)}}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

Calling `perform()` in a constructor runs before the Glimmer component's rendering phase is complete. Services and injections are available, but the task's reactive state changes won't immediately be reflected in the not-yet-rendered template, and any synchronous errors may be harder to handle. The idiomatic alternative is to trigger the task from the template using a custom modifier (like `ember-render-modifiers`'s `did-insert`) or from a user interaction. For data needed immediately on render, use the route's `model()` hook instead.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchPanel extends Component {
  // Task state is INSTANCE-level — fresh for every component creation
  loadMatch = task(async () => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${this.args.matchId}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  // When this component is destroyed and recreated (e.g., route change):
  // - All running instances are cancelled (auto-cancel on destroy)
  // - On recreation: isRunning = false, last = null, performCount = 0
  // - State does NOT persist across destroy/create cycles

  <template>
    {{! On first render: isRunning=false, last=null — no stale state }}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.isRunning}}<p>Loading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.last}}
      <p>{{this.loadMatch.last.value.venue}}</p>
    {{else}}
      <p>Press load to fetch match data</p>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadMatch)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```

Task state is scoped to the component *instance*, not the component class. Every time a component is created, all tasks start fresh: `isRunning` is `false`, `last` is `null`, `performCount` is 0. When the component is destroyed, running tasks are cancelled and the entire task state is garbage-collected with the component. There is no "static" or "class-level" task state that persists across renders. If you need state that survives component destruction, move the task to a service.

```gjs
// In a QUnit test file — testing ember-concurrency tasks
import { module, test } from 'qunit'
import { setupRenderingTest } from 'ember-qunit'
import { render, click, settled } from '@ember/test-helpers'
import { hbs } from 'ember-cli-htmlbars'

module('Integration | Component | score-refresher', function (hooks) {
  setupRenderingTest(hooks)

  test('shows loading state while task runs', async function (assert) {
    await render(hbs`<ScoreRefresher @matchId="m1" />`)

    // Click triggers task.perform()
    click('[data-test-refresh-button]') // intentionally NOT awaited

    // Task is running — check loading state synchronously
    assert.dom('[data-test-loading]').exists()

    // settled() waits for ALL pending tasks, promises, and animations
    await settled()

    // Task complete
    assert.dom('[data-test-loading]').doesNotExist()
    assert.dom('[data-test-score]').hasText('250/6')
  })
})
```

ember-concurrency integrates with Ember's test suite via `settled()`, which waits for all running tasks to complete before assertions run. This eliminates flaky async timing bugs common with raw Promises. Tasks also expose `isRunning` state that can be asserted mid-test by clicking without `await`. For more granular control, `advanceTaskQueue` lets you step through enqueued tasks one at a time. Unlike testing raw `async` methods where you need to stub timers and mock Promises manually, tasks play naturally with Ember's testing infrastructure.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ScoreFetcher extends Component {
  fetchScore = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    return await res.json()
  })

  // performCount increments every time .perform() is called
  // (regardless of whether the call was dropped or not)

  <template>
    {{! Useful for debugging: how many times was perform() called? }}
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">
      Fetch attempts: {{this.fetchScore.performCount}}
    </p>
    <p>Running: {{this.fetchScore.numRunning}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchScore)}}>Fetch Score</button>

    {{! If performCount >> numRunning + numQueued, many calls were dropped }}
    {{#if (gt this.fetchScore.performCount 10)}}
      <p class="text-yellow-500">⚠ High request rate detected</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

`task.performCount` is a counter that increments each time `.perform()` is called, including calls that are dropped or cancelled before running. It's primarily a debugging tool: if `performCount` is significantly higher than `numRunning + numQueued`, many calls are being silently dropped — which might indicate an event handler firing too frequently (e.g., scroll events, resize events). It's also useful in tests to assert that a task was triggered the expected number of times.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

// ❌ Manual @tracked approach — error-prone, verbose
class ManualLoader {
  @tracked isLoading = false
  @tracked data = null
  @tracked error = null

  async load(id) {
    this.isLoading = true
    this.error = null
    try {
      const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`)
      this.data = await res.json() // runs even if component destroyed!
    } catch(e) {
      this.error = e // also runs after destroy!
    } finally {
      this.isLoading = false // isLoading might never reset on cancel
    }
    // No concurrency control — double-click = 2 parallel fetches
  }
}

// ✅ ember-concurrency — all of the above, handled automatically
export default class BetterLoader extends Component {
  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (id) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`)
    return await res.json()
    // isRunning auto-resets, error captured in .last.error,
    // cancelled on destroy, drop prevents double-fetch
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.loadMatch.isRunning}}<p>Loading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.last.error}}<p>Error!</p>{{/if}}
    <p>{{this.loadMatch.lastSuccessful.value.venue}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

The `@tracked isLoading` pattern requires: resetting the flag in `finally`, separate `@tracked error` and `@tracked data` variables, manual concurrency prevention, and manual cancellation in `willDestroy`. That's 10+ lines of boilerplate for every async operation. ember-concurrency replaces all of it with one `task()` call plus a concurrency modifier. It also handles the "update after destroy" bug that the manual approach is always vulnerable to.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class DataImporter extends Component {
  // Composition: enqueue (queue extras) + maxConcurrency (allow N parallel)
  importMatch = task({ enqueue: true, maxConcurrency: 3 }, async (matchData) => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/import/match', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(matchData)
    })
    return await res.json()
  })

  // Composition: drop (ignore extras) + maxConcurrency (allow N parallel)
  // = at most N running, new calls dropped if all N slots busy
  prefetchFixture = task({ drop: true, maxConcurrency: 2 }, async (fixtureId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/fixtures/${fixtureId}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  importAll = () => {
    this.args.matches.forEach(m => this.importMatch.perform(m))
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.importAll}}>Import All</button>
    <p>Running: {{this.importMatch.numRunning}} | Queued: {{this.importMatch.numQueued}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

The modifiers `enqueue`, `drop`, `restartable`, and `keepLatest` are concurrency *policies* that work in combination with `maxConcurrency`. `maxConcurrency` sets the concurrency limit (default 1 when a policy is set), and the policy determines what happens to excess calls. `enqueue + maxConcurrency: 3` = worker pool (3 workers, queue the rest). `drop + maxConcurrency: 3` = allow 3 parallel, drop the rest. `restartable + maxConcurrency: 3` = allow 3, cancel oldest when a 4th arrives. You cannot combine `enqueue` with `restartable` or `keepLatest` — only one queue policy applies.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ScoreCard extends Component {
  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  // 'isRunning', 'isIdle', 'last', etc. are DERIVED STATE
  // They are NOT stored separately — they're computed from the task's internal instances
  // isRunning = numRunning > 0 (derived)
  // isIdle = !isRunning (derived)
  // last = most recent TaskInstance (derived pointer)
  // lastSuccessful = last instance where .isSuccessful === true (derived)

  <template>
    {{! isIdle is simply !isRunning — no extra tracking needed }}
    {{#if this.fetchScore.isIdle}}
      <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchScore this.args.matchId)}}>
        Load Score
      </button>
    {{else}}
      <span class="animate-pulse">Fetching...</span>
    {{/if}}

    {{! All these update automatically because they're derived from tracked internals }}
    <p>Perform count: {{this.fetchScore.performCount}}</p>
    <p>Currently running: {{this.fetchScore.numRunning}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

"Derived state" means that properties like `isRunning`, `isIdle`, and `lastSuccessful` are not stored as independent values — they're computed on-the-fly from the task's internal set of `TaskInstance` objects. `isRunning` is derived by checking if any instance has `isRunning === true`. `lastSuccessful` is derived by finding the most recent instance with `isSuccessful === true`. This means there's no state synchronization bugs: derived state is always mathematically consistent with the actual task instances, and Glimmer's tracking system ensures templates update correctly.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class TournamentStats extends Component {
  // ✅ No memory leak — task is cancelled and dereferenced on component destroy
  loadStats = task(async (tournamentId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/stats`)
    const data = await res.json()
    // Component might be destroyed before this line runs
    // But because this is a task: execution stops at the await above on cancellation
    // The closure, the response, and 'data' are all GC-eligible after task ends
    return data
  })

  // ❌ Memory leak with raw async:
  async loadStatsLeak(id) {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${id}/stats`)
    const data = await res.json()
    // Component is destroyed, but this closure still holds a reference to:
    // - 'this' (the destroyed component)
    // - 'res' (the Response object)
    // - 'data' (the full JSON object)
    // None of these can be GC'd until the Promise chain resolves
    this.stats = data // error: updating destroyed component
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadStats this.args.tournamentId)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```

Raw async method closures capture `this` (the component), keeping it alive in memory until the Promise resolves — even after the component is removed from the DOM. With many pending requests and fast navigation, this accumulates destroyed component instances in memory. ember-concurrency cancels tasks on component destruction, which breaks the closure chain and allows `this`, the response, and all captured variables to be garbage-collected immediately. This is especially important for polling tasks or slow network requests on frequently-navigated routes.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, all } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDayBundle extends Component {
  loadBundle = task(async (matchId) => {
    try {
      // If fetchScore throws, fetchLineup and fetchWeather are abandoned
      const [score, lineup, weather] = await all([
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => {
          if (!r.ok) throw new Error('Score fetch failed')
          return r.json()
        }),
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/lineup`).then(r => r.json()),
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/weather`).then(r => r.json())
      ])
      return { score, lineup, weather }
    } catch (error) {
      // Error from any one of the three propagates here
      console.error('Bundle load failed:', error.message)
      throw error
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.loadBundle.last.error}}
      <p class="text-red-600">Failed: {{this.loadBundle.last.error.message}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadBundle this.args.matchId)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```

`all()` from ember-concurrency behaves like `Promise.all()` on rejection: if any one promise rejects, the entire `all()` rejects with that error and the remaining pending promises are abandoned (not cancelled — native Promises can't be cancelled, but their results are ignored). The error propagates up to the task function where it can be caught in a `try/catch`. This fail-fast behavior is usually desirable: if one critical piece of match data fails, you don't want to render a partial UI with missing data.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, race, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ResilienceDemo extends Component {
  fetchWithFallback = task(async (matchId) => {
    const TIMEOUT_MS = 4000

    const result = await race([
      // Primary: live API
      fetch(`https://live.api/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json()),
      // Fallback: cached CDN version
      fetch(`https://cdn.cache/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json()),
      // Timeout sentinel
      timeout(TIMEOUT_MS).then(() => ({ cached: true, runs: 0, fallback: true }))
    ])

    if (result.fallback) console.warn('Using fallback: timeout reached')
    return result
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchWithFallback this.args.matchId)}}>
      Load
    </button>
    {{#if this.fetchWithFallback.last.value.fallback}}
      <span class="text-yellow-500">⚠ Cached data</span>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

When `race()` resolves (the first promise wins), ember-concurrency stops tracking the remaining promises — their callbacks don't run and they can't update the component. For native Promises this means they complete silently in the background with no effect. For ember-concurrency TaskInstances passed to `race()`, they are actively cancelled. The key benefit is that the "loser" cannot cause side effects or update state after `race()` resolves, unlike `Promise.race()` where losing callbacks still fire.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

// ❌ Antipattern: storing TaskInstance in @tracked
class BadPattern extends Component {
  @tracked currentFetch = null

  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  load = (matchId) => {
    this.currentFetch = this.fetchScore.perform(matchId)
    // Storing instance in @tracked causes extra renders
    // AND task.last already gives you this — duplication!
  }
}

// ✅ Correct: use task.last — already reactive and always current
export default class GoodPattern extends Component {
  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  load = (matchId) => {
    this.fetchScore.perform(matchId)
    // task.last automatically points to this new instance
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.load this.args.matchId)}}>Load</button>
    {{! Use task.last instead of a @tracked instance variable }}
    <p>{{this.fetchScore.last.value.runs}}</p>
    {{#if this.fetchScore.last.isRunning}}<span>Loading...</span>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

`task.last` is already a reactive pointer to the most recent TaskInstance — it updates automatically and triggers template re-renders. Storing the instance in `@tracked` creates redundant state that must stay in sync, causes extra re-renders when the `@tracked` variable is set, and duplicates what `task.last` already provides. The only legitimate reason to hold a TaskInstance reference is for calling `instance.cancel()` to cancel a specific individual execution, and even then you don't need `@tracked` — a plain local variable suffices.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchUpdater extends Component {
  updateScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`)
    const data = await res.json()

    // ✅ No run() needed — ember-concurrency resumes tasks inside the runloop automatically
    // State updates here automatically trigger Glimmer re-renders
    return data

    // ❌ You would NOT need to do this:
    // import { run } from '@ember/runloop'
    // return run(() => data) — unnecessary with ember-concurrency
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.updateScore this.args.matchId)}}>Update</button>
    <p>{{this.updateScore.last.value.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

ember-concurrency automatically wraps task resumptions (the code after each `await`) inside Ember's runloop. This means that when a `fetch()` resolves and your task continues, any `@tracked` mutations or reactive state changes are already batched inside a runloop backfill. You do not need to manually wrap continuations with `run()` or `schedule()`. This is one of the hidden benefits over raw `async/await`, where resumptions after `await fetch(...)` happen outside the runloop and can require manual `run()` calls in older Ember versions.

```gjs
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

// Service-level task: lives for the entire app session
export default class LiveScoreService extends Service {
  // This task is NOT cancelled when individual components are destroyed
  pollLiveScores = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      const res = await fetch('/api/live-scores')
      const data = await res.json()
      this.latestScores = data
      await timeout(10_000)
    }
  })
}

// Component consuming the service — component can be destroyed/recreated
// but polling continues in the service
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class ScoreWidget extends Component {
  @service liveScore

  <template>
    {{! liveScore.pollLiveScores.isRunning — reflects service task state }}
    {{#if this.liveScore.pollLiveScores.isRunning}}
      <span class="text-green-500">● Live</span>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.liveScore.pollLiveScores)}}>Start</button>
  </template>
}
```

Component-level tasks are cancelled when the component is destroyed. Service-level tasks live as long as the service (typically the entire app session). Put tasks in services when: the operation should persist across route changes (live score polling, WebSocket connection management), the data is shared between multiple components, or the task controls app-wide state. Component tasks are appropriate for data local to that component — fetching data for a specific card, handling a form submission. Service tasks handle shared, persistent, or cross-component operations.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDetailPanel extends Component {
  // drop applies ONLY to fetchScore — independent of other tasks
  fetchScore = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/score').then(r => r.json())
  })

  // restartable applies ONLY to fetchCommentary — independent of fetchScore
  fetchCommentary = task({ restartable: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/commentary').then(r => r.json())
  })

  // No modifier — runs concurrently with everything
  fetchWeather = task(async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/weather').then(r => r.json())
  })

  loadAll = () => {
    // All three can run simultaneously — each has its own policy
    this.fetchScore.perform()
    this.fetchCommentary.perform()
    this.fetchWeather.perform()
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.loadAll}}>Load All</button>
    <p>Score: {{#if this.fetchScore.isRunning}}...{{else}}{{this.fetchScore.last.value.runs}}{{/if}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

Concurrency modifiers (`drop`, `restartable`, `keepLatest`, `enqueue`) are scoped to the individual task, not the component class. Two tasks in the same component are completely independent by default — one running does not block or affect the other. To apply a shared policy across multiple tasks, you need `taskGroup`. This means you can have fine-grained control: a `drop` on a save button, a `restartable` on a search box, and an `enqueue` on an event logger, all living on the same component without interfering with each other.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ❌ Raw async event handler — memory leak on route change
class LeakyHandler extends Component {
  handleClick = async (event) => {
    // When route changes mid-fetch:
    // 1. Component is destroyed
    // 2. But this Promise closure keeps 'this' alive
    // 3. GC cannot collect the component
    // 4. When fetch resolves, 'this' is a zombie — alive but not rendered
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    const data = await res.json()
    this.score = data // updating zombie component — memory leak + potential error
  }
}

// ✅ Task-based handler — auto-cancelled on component destroy
export default class SafeHandler extends Component {
  fetchOnClick = task(async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    return await res.json()
    // If component destroyed during fetch: task cancelled, closure released
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchOnClick)}}>Load Score</button>
    <p>{{this.fetchOnClick.last.value.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

A raw `async` function creates a Promise that holds a closure over `this`. If the component is destroyed (route change) before the `await` resolves, the GC sees the Promise still holds a reference to `this` — the component cannot be collected. After resolution, the code after `await` runs on a destroyed object, which may throw errors or silently corrupt state. ember-concurrency tasks register with `@ember/destroyable`, so on component destruction, tasks are cancelled, the closure chain breaks, and `this` becomes eligible for garbage collection immediately.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerCard extends Component {
  // The problem this solves:
  // 1. Component renders, task starts fetching
  // 2. User navigates away — component destroyed
  // 3. Fetch completes 2s later
  // 4. WITHOUT task: code tries to set @tracked on destroyed component → error/leak
  // 5. WITH task: fetch is cancelled at await point on destroy → code never runs

  fetchPlayerStats = task(async (playerId) => {
    await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}`) // ← task cancelled HERE on destroy
    const data = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}/stats`).then(r => r.json())
    // Lines below NEVER run if component destroyed before line above resolves
    return data
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.fetchPlayerStats.isRunning}}
      <div class="animate-pulse">Loading player...</div>
    {{else}}
      <div>{{this.fetchPlayerStats.last.value.battingAverage}}</div>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

In React, `setState()` on an unmounted component throws a warning and can cause subtle bugs. Ember has the same class of bug with `@tracked` mutations on destroyed components. ember-concurrency solves this by cancelling tasks when their owning component is destroyed — code after a cancelled `await` point simply never executes. You get the same protection React's `useEffect` cleanup functions provide, but automatically, without writing any cleanup code. This is one of the strongest arguments for ember-concurrency over manual async patterns in Ember.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class TournamentDashboard extends Component {
  @service router

  // Route-like data loading in a component — full lifecycle control
  loadTournamentData = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {
    const [tournament, fixtures, standings] = await Promise.all([
      fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}`).then(r => r.json()),
      fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/fixtures`).then(r => r.json()),
      fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/standings`).then(r => r.json())
    ])
    return { tournament, fixtures, standings }
  })

  <template>
    {{! Trigger load on first render or arg change }}
    {{#if @tournamentId}}
      {{! Idiomatic: trigger via button or modifier on insert }}
    {{/if}}

    {{#if this.loadTournamentData.isRunning}}
      <div class="min-h-screen flex items-center justify-center">
        <span class="animate-spin text-4xl">⟳</span>
      </div>
    {{else if this.loadTournamentData.last.error}}
      <p class="text-red-500">Failed to load tournament</p>
    {{else if this.loadTournamentData.lastSuccessful}}
      <h1>{{this.loadTournamentData.lastSuccessful.value.tournament.name}}</h1>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

Ember's route `model()` hook is synchronous-first and doesn't expose loading/error state in components — it relies on route-level `loading` and `error` substates. Tasks offer component-level loading state, error handling, cancellation, and retry — without requiring route substate configuration. They're the community standard for any data loading that happens in response to user interaction (tab switches, filter changes, pagination) or needs fine-grained loading UI beyond a route-level spinner.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class TrafficControlDemo extends Component {
  // 🚦 TRAFFIC CONTROL METAPHOR:
  // Imagine task.perform() = a car arriving at a checkpoint
  // The modifier = the traffic policy at that checkpoint

  // 🔴 drop: "Checkpoint full, turn around" — car is rejected
  saveScore = task({ drop: true }, async (score) => {
    await fetch('/api/score', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(score) })
  })

  // 🔄 restartable: "New car arrives, push old car back to start" — old run cancelled
  searchPlayer = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {
    await fetch(`/api/players?q=${query}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  // 📋 enqueue: "Take a number, wait in line" — everyone served in order
  logBallEvent = task({ enqueue: true }, async (event) => {
    await fetch('/api/events', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(event) })
  })

  // 💾 keepLatest: "You go, I'll remember the last arrival only" — current finishes, then latest
  autoSave = task({ keepLatest: true }, async (data) => {
    await fetch('/api/save', { method: 'PUT', body: JSON.stringify(data) })
  })

  // 🚀 maxConcurrency (3): "3 lanes open" — 3 cars at a time, rest follow their policy
  fetchFixture = task({ enqueue: true, maxConcurrency: 3 }, async (id) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/fixtures/${id}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  <template><p>Traffic control demo — see code comments</p></template>
}
```

Think of `task.perform()` as a car arriving at a traffic checkpoint, and the modifier as the checkpoint's policy. **drop** = "checkpoint full, turn around" — new arrivals are rejected and the current car finishes. **restartable** = "priority lane" — the newest car pushes the current one off the road and takes its place. **enqueue** = "take a number" — everyone queues politely and is served in order. **keepLatest** = "skip the queue, but only one reservation" — the current car finishes, and the most recently-arrived waiting car goes next. **maxConcurrency** = "number of open lanes" — how many cars can pass simultaneously before the policy kicks in.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { TaskCancelation } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchLoaderComponent extends Component {
  fetchMatch = task(async (matchId) => {
    try {
      const data = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
      return await data.json()
    } catch (e) {
      if (e instanceof TaskCancelation) {
        // Task was cancelled — not an error, do NOT log or re-throw
        console.log('Task cancelled cleanly')
        return
      }
      // Genuine network or parsing error
      console.error('Match fetch failed:', e.message)
      throw e
    }
  })
}
```
ember-concurrency throws a `TaskCancelation` object when a task is cancelled — this is NOT a subclass of `Error`. If you have a generic `catch (e)` block, you must explicitly check `e instanceof TaskCancelation` before treating it as a real error. Genuine errors (network failures, JSON parse errors) should be re-thrown or handled normally. Mixing up the two causes false error logs and broken UI states.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { TaskCancelation } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ScoreboardComponent extends Component {
  loadScores = task(async () => {
    try {
      const res = await fetch('/api/scores')
      return await res.json()
    } catch (e) {
      // ✅ CORRECT — swallow cancellation silently
      if (e instanceof TaskCancelation) return

      // ✅ Only re-throw real errors
      throw e
    }
  })
}
```
`TaskCancelation` is a plain object, not an `Error` instance — it has no stack trace and is not meant to bubble up. Re-throwing it causes uncaught exception warnings in the console and can crash promise chains that don't expect it. ember-concurrency uses it purely as a control-flow signal to stop execution. Always check for it first in any `catch` block and return early without re-throwing.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { TaskCancelation } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerStatsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked errorMessage = null

  loadPlayerStats = task(async (playerId) => {
    this.errorMessage = null
    try {
      const res = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}/stats`)
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`)
      return await res.json()
    } catch (e) {
      if (e instanceof TaskCancelation) {
        // Silently exit — user navigated away or task restarted
        return
      }
      // Real error — update UI
      this.errorMessage = `Failed to load stats: ${e.message}`
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.errorMessage}}
      <p class="text-red-500">{{this.errorMessage}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadPlayerStats.isRunning}}
      <p>Loading...</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Use `e instanceof TaskCancelation` as the first guard in your catch block. If it matches, return immediately and skip all error-handling logic. Only after ruling out cancellation should you update `@tracked` error state or re-throw. This pattern keeps your error UI clean — cancellations are silent internal events, not user-facing failures.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class LiveScoreComponent extends Component {
  // ❌ AVOID — raw setTimeout leaks and is not cancellation-aware
  // pollScore = task(async () => {
  //   while (true) {
  //     await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 5000))
  //     await this.fetchScore()
  //   }
  // })

  // ✅ CORRECT — timeout() is cancellation-aware
  pollScore = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      await timeout(5000)
      const res = await fetch('/api/live-score')
      return await res.json()
    }
  })
}
```
`timeout()` from ember-concurrency is a yieldable — when the task is cancelled, the `timeout()` call is immediately aborted and no further code runs. A raw `setTimeout` wrapped in a Promise has no such awareness: even after cancellation, the timer fires and your callback runs, potentially causing state mutations on a destroyed component. In tests, `timeout()` also integrates with Ember's test helpers and can be fast-forwarded with `advanceTime`.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerSearchComponent extends Component {
  searchPlayers = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {
    // Wait 300ms — if user types again, this task restarts from here
    await timeout(300)
    const res = await fetch(`/api/players?q=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    <input
      type="text"
      placeholder="Search player..."
      {{on "input" (fn (perform this.searchPlayers) value)}}
    />
    {{#if this.searchPlayers.isRunning}}
      <p>Searching...</p>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if this.searchPlayers.last.value}}
      {{#each this.searchPlayers.last.value as |player|}}
        <p>{{player.name}}</p>
      {{/each}}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
With `restartable`, each new `perform()` cancels the currently running instance before starting fresh. Placing `await timeout(300)` at the top means rapid keystrokes cancel and restart the task repeatedly — the API call only fires after the user pauses for 300ms. This is classic debounce behavior with zero manual `clearTimeout` / `setTimeout` bookkeeping.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class OversTrackerComponent extends Component {
  // ⚠️ drop — if a fetch is running when user changes over, new request is silently ignored
  // fetchOver = task({ drop: true }, async (overId) => { ... })

  // ✅ keepLatest — queues the latest request, runs it after current finishes
  fetchOver = task({ keepLatest: true }, async (overId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/overs/${overId}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    {{#each @overs as |over|}}
      <button {{on "click" (fn (perform this.fetchOver) over.id)}}>
        Over {{over.number}}
      </button>
    {{/each}}
    {{#if this.fetchOver.last.value}}
      <p>Runs: {{this.fetchOver.last.value.runs}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
`drop` silently ignores any new `perform()` while the task is running — the user's last action is lost. `keepLatest` queues exactly one pending perform (the most recent), and runs it immediately after the current instance finishes. This guarantees the UI always reflects the user's last intent. Use `drop` only when ignoring subsequent requests is intentional (e.g. a one-time submit button).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, taskGroup } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDashboardComponent extends Component {
  dataLoaders = taskGroup({ drop: true })

  fetchBatsmen = task({ group: this.dataLoaders }, async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/batsmen')
    return await res.json()
  })

  fetchBowlers = task({ group: this.dataLoaders }, async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/bowlers')
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchBatsmen)}}>Load Batsmen</button>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchBowlers)}}>Load Bowlers</button>

    {{! isRunning is true if EITHER task is running }}
    {{#if this.dataLoaders.isRunning}}
      <p class="text-yellow-500">Loading match data...</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
`taskGroup.isRunning` returns `true` if **any** task in the group is currently running. This is useful for a single loading indicator that covers multiple async operations. The group also applies its concurrency modifier (`drop`, `enqueue`, etc.) across all member tasks — so `drop` on the group prevents any member from running while another is active.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ❌ WRONG — tasks defined in constructor break ember-concurrency's decorator system
// export default class BadComponent extends Component {
//   constructor(owner, args) {
//     super(owner, args)
//     this.fetchScore = task(async () => { ... })  // Does not wire up properly
//   }
// }

// ✅ CORRECT — class field definition
export default class ScoreComponent extends Component {
  fetchScore = task(async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    return await res.json()
  })
}
```
ember-concurrency's `task()` function uses class field initializer semantics to attach metadata to the instance and register itself with the owner for lifecycle management (including auto-cancellation on `willDestroy`). Defining tasks in the `constructor` bypasses this wiring, causing tasks to not cancel on component teardown and `isRunning` / `last` state to not be reactive. Always use class field syntax.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ❌ VERBOSE — manual flags
// @tracked isLoading = false
// @tracked hasError = false
// @tracked matchData = null

// ✅ CLEAN — task state is reactive out of the box
export default class MatchDetailComponent extends Component {
  loadMatch = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to load match')
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (fn (perform this.loadMatch) @matchId)}}>
