Perform **eagerly** (on mount via `didInsert`) when the component's primary purpose is to display that data — the user expects to see it immediately. Perform **lazily** (on user action) when the data is optional, expensive, or only needed after a specific interaction (e.g. expanding a panel, clicking a 'Load More' button). Lazy loading improves initial render performance and reduces unnecessary API calls.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, taskGroup } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ✅ OPTION A — taskGroup drop: prevents ANY member from running while any other runs
export default class MatchDataComponent extends Component {
  loaders = taskGroup({ drop: true })

  fetchScorecard = task({ group: this.loaders }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/scorecard').then(r => r.json())
  })

  fetchLineup = task({ group: this.loaders }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/lineup').then(r => r.json())
  })
}

// ✅ OPTION B — individual drop: each task has its own independent concurrency
// fetchScorecard = task({ drop: true }, async () => { ... })
// fetchLineup = task({ drop: true }, async () => { ... })
// Running fetchScorecard does NOT drop fetchLineup performs
```
Use `taskGroup drop` when running **any** member task should block all others — e.g. a pipeline where tasks share the same resource. Use **individual `drop`** on each task when tasks are independent and should each manage their own concurrency separately. `taskGroup` is more restrictive; individual modifiers are more granular. Choose based on whether the tasks compete for the same resource.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ⚠️ @tracked only — no double-click protection, no error rollback
// @action async addRuns(runs) {
//   this.totalRuns += runs
//   await fetch('/api/score/add', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify({ runs }) })
// }

// ✅ task — drop prevents double-click, catch enables rollback
export default class ScorecardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked totalRuns = this.args.initialRuns

  addRuns = task({ drop: true }, async (runs) => {
    const previous = this.totalRuns
    this.totalRuns += runs  // optimistic update
    try {
      await fetch('/api/score/add', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify({ runs }) })
    } catch {
      this.totalRuns = previous  // rollback on failure
    }
  })

  <template>
    <p>Score: {{this.totalRuns}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" (fn (perform this.addRuns) 4)}}>
      +4 Runs
    </button>
  </template>
}
```
Use a `task` for optimistic updates. `drop` prevents concurrent conflicting updates. The snapshot-and-rollback pattern in `catch` reverts the optimistic change if the server rejects it. A plain `@tracked` action has no double-click protection and no structured rollback mechanism — two rapid clicks would apply the optimistic update twice before the first server response arrives.

