// ⚠️ task in HELPER — non-standard, limited, avoid
// Helpers in Glimmer are pure functions or resource-based
// They don't have willDestroy lifecycle for auto-cancellation
// import { helper } from '@ember/component/helper'
// export default helper(([matchId]) => { ... }) // no task support
```
Put data-fetching tasks in **components or services** — never in helpers. Ember helpers (both classic and Glimmer) are designed for pure value transformations, not async side effects. They lack the lifecycle hooks (`willDestroy`) that ember-concurrency needs for auto-cancellation. If you need data fetching tied to a template expression, use ember-resources (a separate addon) or move the task into the component or an injected service.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDisplayComponent extends Component {
  fetchMatch = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`)
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  <template>
    {{! task.last?.value — value from most recent run, null if it errored }}
    {{#if this.fetchMatch.last.value}}
      <p>Latest: {{this.fetchMatch.last.value.title}}</p>
    {{/if}}

    {{! task.lastSuccessful?.value — value from last SUCCESSFUL run }}
    {{! Persists even if a subsequent run errors — shows stale-but-valid data }}
    {{#if this.fetchMatch.lastSuccessful.value}}
      <p>Last good: {{this.fetchMatch.lastSuccessful.value.title}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Use `task.last?.value` when you only want to show data from the most recent run and are fine showing nothing if it errored. Use `task.lastSuccessful?.value` when you want to show the last known-good result even if a subsequent refresh fails — this is the better UX for live data panels where showing stale data is preferable to showing nothing. Both are reactive and require no `@tracked` variables.

```gjs
