Chart components should be pure and presentational — they render whatever data they receive and know nothing about how it was fetched. This makes them reusable (same chart for live and historical data), testable (just pass mock data), and composable (parent decides when/how to load). Put the task in the parent component or route that owns the page's data lifecycle. Only put a task inside a chart component if the chart has a unique, non-shareable data source that no parent would reasonably own.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: service-level subscription for shared, app-wide stream
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchStreamService extends Service {
  @tracked latestEvent = null
  socket = null

  connect = task(async (matchId) => {
    this.socket = new WebSocket(`wss://api.spordium.com/match/${matchId}/stream`)
    await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      this.socket.onopen = resolve
      this.socket.onerror = reject
    })
    this.socket.onmessage = (e) => {
      this.latestEvent = JSON.parse(e.data)
    }
  })

  disconnect() {
    this.socket?.close()
    this.connect.cancelAll()
  }
}

// Any component just reads:
// @service matchStream;
// {{this.matchStream.latestEvent.description}}
```

Put the WebSocket subscription in a service when multiple components (scorecard, commentary feed, run rate chart) all need the same live events. A component-level task would create duplicate connections — one per component that mounts. A service creates one connection, shares it reactively via `@tracked` properties, and tears it down cleanly when the service is destroyed. Use a component-level task only for subscriptions that are truly private to that single component and never shared.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: task — upload is async, can fail, needs progress indication
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerPhotoUploadComponent extends Component {
  @tracked previewUrl = null

  uploadPhoto = task(async (file) => {
    this.previewUrl = URL.createObjectURL(file)
    const formData = new FormData()
    formData.append('photo', file)
    await fetch(`/api/player/${this.args.playerId}/photo`, {
      method: 'POST',
      body: formData
    })
    this.args.onUploadComplete()
  })

  handleFileChange = (e) => {
    const file = e.target.files[0]
    if (file) this.uploadPhoto.perform(file)
  }

  <template>
    <input type="file" accept="image/*" {{on "change" this.handleFileChange}} />
    {{#if this.previewUrl}}<img src={{this.previewUrl}} alt="Preview" />{{/if}}
    {{#if this.uploadPhoto.isRunning}}<p>Uploading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.uploadPhoto.last.error}}<p class="text-red-500">Upload failed. Try again.</p>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

File uploads are async network operations that can take several seconds and fail for many reasons (file too large, network error, server error). A task gives you `isRunning` for a loading state, `last.error` for failure messages, and prevents double submission if the user somehow triggers the input twice. A plain `@action` with no task wrapper forces you to manually manage an `isUploading` flag, `uploadError` tracker, and cleanup — all of which the task provides for free.

```gjs
// restartable — cancels current, starts fresh immediately
searchPlayers = task({ restartable: true }, async (query) => {
  await timeout(300)
  this.results = await fetch(`/api/players?q=${query}`).then(r => r.json())
})
// Keystroke at t=0: starts, waits 300ms
// Keystroke at t=200: CANCELS previous, starts again, waits 300ms from t=200
// Result arrives at t=500 (200+300)

// keepLatest — lets current finish, queues ONE replacement
searchPlayers = task({ keepLatest: true }, async (query) => {
  await timeout(300)
  this.results = await fetch(`/api/players?q=${query}`).then(r => r.json())
})
// Keystroke at t=0: starts, waits 300ms
// Keystroke at t=200: queued (current keeps running)
// First result at t=300 (stale query!), then runs queued at t=300
// Latest result at t=600
```

**`restartable` shows the latest result faster** for search inputs. It cancels the in-flight task on every keystroke and restarts the debounce timer, so the total latency from the last keystroke to the result is always just one debounce period (300ms) plus one API round-trip. `keepLatest` lets the current task finish first, so results are delayed by the remaining time of the previous task plus a full new task run — often 2× slower. Use `restartable` for search, typeahead, and any input where only the most recent value matters. Use `keepLatest` when you want the current operation to always complete (e.g., a save in progress).

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: combine both — events for immediate detection, task for verification
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ConnectivityService extends Service {
  @tracked isOnline = navigator.onLine

  constructor(...args) {
    super(...args)
    window.addEventListener('online', () => this.verifyConnection.perform())
    window.addEventListener('offline', () => { this.isOnline = false })
    this.verifyConnection.perform()
  }

  verifyConnection = task({ restartable: true }, async () => {
    try {
      await fetch('/api/health', { cache: 'no-store', signal: AbortSignal.timeout(3000) })
      this.isOnline = true
    } catch {
      this.isOnline = false
    }
  })

  pollHealth = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      await timeout(30000)
      await this.verifyConnection.perform()
    }
  })
}
```

`navigator.onLine` reacts instantly to network interface changes but is unreliable — it can be `true` even when the actual internet is unreachable (connected to a router with no WAN). A task that pings a real endpoint verifies true connectivity but adds latency. The best pattern combines both: listen to browser events for immediate `false` detection (device goes offline), and use a task to verify `true` status by actually hitting your API. For a live cricket score app where stale data is confusing, this dual approach is essential.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: task for async validation (server roundtrip required)
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerRegistrationComponent extends Component {
  @tracked jerseyNumber = ''
  @tracked jerseyError = null

  validateJersey = task({ restartable: true }, async (value) => {
    this.jerseyError = null
    await timeout(400)
    if (!value || isNaN(value)) {
      this.jerseyError = 'Must be a valid number'
      return
    }
    const { available } = await fetch(`/api/team/${this.args.teamId}/jersey/${value}/available`)
      .then(r => r.json())
    this.jerseyError = available ? null : 'Jersey number already taken'
  })

  handleInput = (e) => {
    this.jerseyNumber = e.target.value
    this.validateJersey.perform(e.target.value)
  }

  <template>
    <input value={{this.jerseyNumber}} {{on "input" this.handleInput}} />
    {{#if this.validateJersey.isRunning}}<span>Checking...</span>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.jerseyError}}<p class="text-red-500">{{this.jerseyError}}</p>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

Synchronous getters cannot perform async work — if uniqueness requires a server check, you must use a task. Use synchronous getters for format validation (is it a number? is it in range 1–99?) and reserve the task for the async uniqueness check. A `restartable` task with a debounce is ideal: it cancels mid-flight on each keystroke, so only one API call runs at a time and the 'Checking...' spinner only appears after the user has paused typing.

```gjs
// ✅ RECOMMENDED: task — async, handles all permission states, surfaces errors
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class AlertSettingsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked permissionStatus = Notification.permission

  requestAlertPermission = task(async () => {
    if (this.permissionStatus === 'granted') return
    const result = await Notification.requestPermission()
    this.permissionStatus = result
    if (result === 'granted') {
      this.args.onPermissionGranted()
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if (eq this.permissionStatus 'granted')}}
      <p class="text-green-600">✓ Match alerts enabled</p>
    {{else if (eq this.permissionStatus 'denied')}}
      <p class="text-red-500">Alerts blocked. Enable in browser settings.</p>
    {{else}}
      <button {{on "click" (perform this.requestAlertPermission)}}>
        Enable Match Alerts
      </button>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

`Notification.requestPermission()` returns a promise (modern browsers) so a task is the natural wrapper. It gives you `isRunning` while the browser permission dialog is visible, `last.error` if the API throws, and prevents double-requesting if the user clicks the button repeatedly. Calling it directly in an `@action` works for simple cases but gives you no loading state and no built-in double-click prevention. Always check `Notification.permission` before requesting to avoid re-prompting users who have already responded.

